24    /**
25    * Factory that creates instances of DateTimeFormatter based on the ISO8601 standard.
26    * <p>
27    * Date-time formatting is performed by the {@link DateTimeFormatter} class.
28    * Three classes provide factory methods to create formatters, and this is one.
29    * The others are {@link DateTimeFormat} and {@link DateTimeFormatterBuilder}.
30    * <p>
31    * ISO8601 is the international standard for data interchange. It defines a
32    * framework, rather than an absolute standard. As a result this provider has a
33    * number of methods that represent common uses of the framework. The most common
34    * formats are {@link #date() date}, {@link #time() time}, and {@link #dateTime() dateTime}.
35    * <p>
36    * For example, to format a date time in ISO format:
37    * <pre>
38    * DateTime dt = new DateTime();
39    * DateTimeFormatter fmt = ISODateTimeFormat.dateTime();
40    * String str = fmt.print(dt);
41    * </pre>
42    * <p>
43    * Note that these formatters mostly follow the ISO8601 standard for printing.
44    * For parsing, the formatters are more lenient and allow formats that are not
45    * in strict compliance with the standard.
46    * <p>
47    * It is important to understand that these formatters are not linked to
48    * the <code>ISOChronology</code>. These formatters may be used with any
49    * chronology, however there may be certain side effects with more unusual
50    * chronologies. For example, the ISO formatters rely on dayOfWeek being
51    * single digit, dayOfMonth being two digit and dayOfYear being three digit.
52    * A chronology with a ten day week would thus cause issues. However, in
53    * general, it is safe to use these formatters with other chronologies.
54    * <p>
55    * ISODateTimeFormat is thread-safe and immutable, and the formatters it
56    * returns are as well.
57    *
58    * @author Brian S O'Neill
59    * @see DateTimeFormat
60    * @see DateTimeFormatterBuilder
61    * @since 1.0
62    */
 
96.8% Uncovered Elements: 11 (345) Complexity: 131 Complexity Density: 0.67

76    /**
77    * Returns a formatter that outputs only those fields specified.
78    * <p>
79    * This method examines the fields provided and returns an ISO-style
80    * formatter that best fits. This can be useful for outputting
81    * less-common ISO styles, such as YearMonth (YYYY-MM) or MonthDay (--MM-DD).
82    * <p>
83    * Note that parsing is often not supported by the resulting formatter, especially in basic mode.
84    * <p>
85    * The list provided may have overlapping fields, such as dayOfWeek and
86    * dayOfMonth. In this case, the style is chosen based on the following
87    * list, thus in the example, the calendar style is chosen as dayOfMonth
88    * is higher in priority than dayOfWeek:
89    * <ul>
90    * <li>monthOfYear - calendar date style
91    * <li>dayOfYear - ordinal date style
92    * <li>weekOfWeekYear - week date style
93    * <li>dayOfMonth - calendar date style
94    * <li>dayOfWeek - week date style
95    * <li>year
96    * <li>weekyear
97    * </ul>
98    * The supported formats are:
99    * <pre>
100    * Extended Basic Fields
101    * 2005-03-25 20050325 year/monthOfYear/dayOfMonth
102    * 2005-03 2005-03 year/monthOfYear
103    * 2005--25 2005--25 year/dayOfMonth *
104    * 2005 2005 year
105    * --03-25 --0325 monthOfYear/dayOfMonth
106    * --03 --03 monthOfYear
107    * ---03 ---03 dayOfMonth
108    * 2005-084 2005084 year/dayOfYear
109    * -084 -084 dayOfYear
110    * 2005-W12-5 2005W125 weekyear/weekOfWeekyear/dayOfWeek
111    * 2005-W-5 2005W-5 weekyear/dayOfWeek *
112    * 2005-W12 2005W12 weekyear/weekOfWeekyear
113    * -W12-5 -W125 weekOfWeekyear/dayOfWeek
114    * -W12 -W12 weekOfWeekyear
115    * -W-5 -W-5 dayOfWeek
116    * 10:20:30.040 102030.040 hour/minute/second/milli
117    * 10:20:30 102030 hour/minute/second
118    * 10:20 1020 hour/minute
119    * 10 10 hour
120    * -20:30.040 -2030.040 minute/second/milli
121    * -20:30 -2030 minute/second
122    * -20 -20 minute
123    * --30.040 --30.040 second/milli
124    * --30 --30 second
125    * ---.040 ---.040 milli *
126    * 10-30.040 10-30.040 hour/second/milli *
127    * 10:20-.040 1020-.040 hour/minute/milli *
128    * 10-30 10-30 hour/second *
129    * 10--.040 10--.040 hour/milli *
130    * -20-.040 -20-.040 minute/milli *
131    * plus datetime formats like {date}T{time}
132    * </pre>
133    * * indicates that this is not an official ISO format and can be excluded
134    * by passing in <code>strictISO</code> as <code>true</code>.
135    * <p>
136    * This method can side effect the input collection of fields.
137    * If the input collection is modifiable, then each field that was added to
138    * the formatter will be removed from the collection, including any duplicates.
139    * If the input collection is unmodifiable then no side effect occurs.
140    * <p>
141    * This side effect processing is useful if you need to know whether all
142    * the fields were converted into the formatter or not. To achieve this,
143    * pass in a modifiable list, and check that it is empty on exit.
144    *
145    * @param fields the fields to get a formatter for, not null,
146    * updated by the method call unless unmodifiable,
147    * removing those fields built in the formatter
148    * @param extended true to use the extended format (with separators)
149    * @param strictISO true to stick exactly to ISO8601, false to include additional formats
150    * @return a suitable formatter
151    * @throws IllegalArgumentException if there is no format for the fields
152    * @since 1.1
153    */
